00:24:46,760 --> 00:24:59,804
They are just nervous that if it goes further out where people might not want a two family or a second floor built or that they would question out of fear that they wouldn't get this.

206
00:24:59,984 --> 00:25:01,525
This is one of their biggest concerns.

207
00:25:02,965 --> 00:25:18,277
So I like the idea that, you know, the idea that putting it for the six or more units, I think that that's probably our biggest fear that we've heard here is that, the fear that things are happening so fast, so quick, and notifying people.

208
00:25:18,657 --> 00:25:29,186
But my question is ultimately, it can't be, the ordinance can't be written, excuse me, I'm getting off track, but the question is that,

209
00:25:30,913 --> 00:25:45,038
If this, what we have in line right now, if this is adopted, it still goes to the state level, and the state level, it's just something that could be heard, but won't be, can't be used as judgment.

210
00:25:45,058 --> 00:25:47,199
All right.

211
00:25:47,279 --> 00:25:49,820
It's a valid concern, and it gets a little bit confusing.

212
00:25:52,062 --> 00:25:53,163
But it runs this way.

213
00:25:54,123 --> 00:25:56,085
The state statute is the core.

214
00:25:56,765 --> 00:25:57,766
It is required.

215
00:25:58,186 --> 00:25:59,287
It is compulsory.

216
00:25:59,767 --> 00:26:08,953
And the state statute says that notice must be given to abutters or abutters to abutters, and those across the street, within 300 feet.

217
00:26:09,194 --> 00:26:10,054
That's the core.

218
00:26:10,635 --> 00:26:11,495
That doesn't change.

219
00:26:11,995 --> 00:26:12,936
And that's required.

220
00:26:13,737 --> 00:26:18,140
This would be additional requirement, a local option.

221
00:26:18,640 --> 00:26:19,260
Not local option.

222
00:26:19,280 --> 00:26:20,101
That's not the way to put it.

223
00:26:20,141 --> 00:26:21,142
Local requirement.

224
00:26:22,142 --> 00:26:29,987
And, if it's passed by the council, ultimately, then the Board of Appeals would have to implement that notice requirement.

225
00:26:30,527 --> 00:26:33,629
Now, as I said at the beginning, if Mr. Jones or Ms.

226
00:26:33,689 --> 00:26:41,394
Smith is not happy with the approval of a variance or whatever it is, and then appeals to the court,

227
00:26:42,368 --> 00:26:49,410
If they're not in that core area, they would not be considered to be a party in interest because of their location.

228
00:26:49,671 --> 00:26:51,971
There may be some other reasons that they could have standing.

229
00:26:52,011 --> 00:26:53,052
I'm not saying that they wouldn't.

230
00:26:53,712 --> 00:26:59,614
But their location, if they're outside of that core area, would not give them proper standing.

231
00:27:00,234 --> 00:27:06,797
What it would do is mean that from a local point of view, here in Medford, they would get some notification.

232
00:27:07,097 --> 00:27:07,837
Now here's the thing.

233
00:27:08,505 --> 00:27:11,006
There's nothing bad in anything that anybody just said.

234
00:27:11,646 --> 00:27:18,288
Because here's, I don't want to sound like Pollyanna, but I've been part of municipal government for 34 years.

235
00:27:18,628 --> 00:27:24,230
And one of the common threads that goes through as a criticism is, I didn't know.

236
00:27:25,751 --> 00:27:26,791
When did that happen?

237
00:27:28,792 --> 00:27:29,652
Who did that?

238
00:27:30,661 --> 00:27:38,888
And when that occurs, what you have is a lessening of the quantum of trust that a resident has in the local government.

239
00:27:40,249 --> 00:27:49,417
This measure will address that in a fashion by giving greater notice, even if it doesn't give legal teeth.

240
00:27:51,216 --> 00:27:55,397
The benefit of fine-tuning it is that Ms.

241
00:27:55,477 --> 00:28:09,081
Jones or Mr. Smith, who wants to extend a bedroom for maybe an elderly member of their family, won't have to go through hoops if this only applies to larger projects.

242
00:28:09,661 --> 00:28:21,633
And generally speaking, I don't hear, in my 34 years, I don't hear, I didn't know about that when we're talking about a neighbor increasing the size of their house a little bit for a family reason.

243
00:28:22,353 --> 00:28:25,736
When you hear it, you already know the projects that you hear it on.

244
00:28:25,756 --> 00:28:27,278
They don't have to say what they are.

245
00:28:28,519 --> 00:28:39,131
But they're the larger projects, the ones that have multiple units, the ones that have traffic impact, which, by the way, is an element or an issue that has to be reviewed in site plan review.

246
00:28:39,432 --> 00:28:39,852
Traffic.

247
00:28:40,753 --> 00:28:43,917
And those are the ones where people say, I didn't know that.

248
00:28:44,894 --> 00:28:48,816
And so there's where, if there is any fine-tuning, that may be a benefit.

249
00:28:49,616 --> 00:29:04,864
The other thing is, since this is an amendment to the zoning ordinance, then this would have to go, assuming that it left the launching pad here at the city council, it would have to go to the planning board for a public hearing.

250
00:29:05,564 --> 00:29:11,267
So the input of others could be received, too, and then the planning board makes its recommendation back to the council.

251
00:29:11,987 --> 00:29:13,408
Well, that's a pretty good thing to have.

252
00:29:14,342 --> 00:29:18,607
public input on whether or not to extend public notification.

253
00:29:18,968 --> 00:29:21,131
Seems to me that that fits together like Legos.

254
00:29:22,283 --> 00:29:23,604
So that's what I'd say.

255
00:29:24,165 --> 00:29:33,612
Thank you very much for my trivial response, but I think, again, I know that my council colleague put together a very thoughtful ordinance.

256
00:29:33,732 --> 00:29:50,986
I think that the concerns that Councilor Falco brought up with the site plan review, I would definitely support this if, because I think we all sit here and understand the phone calls we get with the bigger developments that come out that are affecting the zoning that's affecting our

257
00:29:51,566 --> 00:30:00,096
our community so I will support this wholeheartedly if we can that I agree with what council Falco stated with

258
00:30:03,745 --> 00:30:09,447
site plan reviews, anything over six units, that this would be implemented.

259
00:30:09,507 --> 00:30:25,192
So I think that wouldn't affect the phone calls I got that were questioning and nervousness and the fear of our neighbors that how this could affect a homeowner who was looking to improve their home and their future.

260
00:30:25,252 --> 00:30:29,133
So I hope that helps with the other Brianna, but thank you.

261
00:30:30,333 --> 00:30:36,837
The clerk has informed me that the cost is approximately a dollar to send out a mailing to all the homes.

262
00:30:37,217 --> 00:30:41,679
And then it's another dollar because he has to also mail them the decision that is written.

263
00:30:42,079 --> 00:30:44,321
So it will be about two dollars per household.

264
00:30:45,321 --> 00:30:45,842
Councillor Knight.

265
00:30:46,462 --> 00:30:47,662
Mr. President, thank you very much.

266
00:30:50,505 --> 00:31:05,311
City Solicitor Rumley has framed this in a pretty basic and outright fashion, that the steps that we need to go through, if we decide to adopt the zoning amendment this evening, that it goes to the Community Development Board for a public hearing.

267
00:31:06,752 --> 00:31:11,374
So, in looking at the action that we're taking here as a body tonight, I think we're torn.

268
00:31:11,414 --> 00:31:13,215
I mean, we've all sat here and we've all talked about

269
00:31:14,035 --> 00:31:14,976
requirements for notice.

270
00:31:15,016 --> 00:31:19,298
We want more people to know what's going on in their neighborhood, and we don't want to hurt people at the same time, Mr. President.

271
00:31:19,318 --> 00:31:30,746
So here we have a proposal that would increase the notification ramifications by about 100 yards, and then also add everybody that lives in that jurisdiction to the notification requirements.

272
00:31:31,286 --> 00:31:41,232
I think it might be in our best interest to send the paper as authored to the Community Development Board for their input at a public hearing, get the information and the input that they can secure,

273
00:31:42,353 --> 00:31:47,874
And when they bring it back to us, then we'll be in a better position to make a determination as to what language changes we would like to see made.

274
00:31:48,474 --> 00:32:02,897
I certainly would agree that I think projects requiring site plan review only would be something that I'd be very supportive of, Mr. President, but I don't think that that's going to be something that's going to be a hindrance for me this evening for supporting this measure and sending it to the Community Development Board for a public hearing and for their input.

275
00:32:03,857 --> 00:32:04,158
Thank you.

276
00:32:05,158 --> 00:32:05,958
Councilor Del Rosso.

277
00:32:08,818 --> 00:32:09,479
Councilor Del Rosso.

278
00:32:09,859 --> 00:32:11,059
Yes, thank you, Mr. President.

279
00:32:16,428 --> 00:32:26,979
I'm generally in favor of this expanded notification, but if I could, Mr. President, through the chair to the solicitor, ask a question regarding the amendment.

280
00:32:28,061 --> 00:32:28,921
My question is this.

281
00:32:30,335 --> 00:32:55,941
It was stated by Councilor Lungo Kern that, and I'm sure this is true without a doubt, that we're not seeking to harm the homeowner in this ordinance, but if we put a stipulation on the expansion of the notification to those

282
00:32:57,793 --> 00:33:07,061
projects that require site plan review, i.e., a way of getting at the bigger projects, is that a signaling that we're aiming to harm someone?

283
00:33:07,721 --> 00:33:08,782
Could it be read as that?

284
00:33:09,103 --> 00:33:10,584
So are we targeting someone?

285
00:33:10,684 --> 00:33:12,425
Are we being prejudicial?

286
00:33:12,525 --> 00:33:16,309
So what applies to one thing, should it apply to all?

287
00:33:16,389 --> 00:33:17,590
That's just my question.

288
00:33:19,611 --> 00:33:21,053
I get the question, and I'd say this.

289
00:33:22,296 --> 00:33:27,542
First of all, the legislative discretion of a body like the City Council is indeed that.

290
00:33:28,223 --> 00:33:37,313
If you exercise that discretion in a reasonable way, based upon considerations before you, it would not be arbitrary, nor would it be discriminatory.

291
00:33:37,933 --> 00:33:42,076
In addition, the greater concern of the public is always the larger projects.

292
00:33:42,697 --> 00:33:46,139
It's not the smaller ones that have been alluded to here tonight.

293
00:33:46,680 --> 00:33:54,545
So indeed, if a large developer said, I'm being prejudiced by having to notice this many people, I would say, so what?

294
00:33:56,587 --> 00:34:00,009
Take your shot, bring us to court, and let's see what happens.

295
00:34:01,911 --> 00:34:02,251
Thank you.

296
00:34:02,671 --> 00:34:02,972
You're welcome.

297
00:34:03,532 --> 00:34:04,613
Thank you, Mr. President.

298
00:34:05,939 --> 00:34:06,659
Council Member Kern.

299
00:34:06,940 --> 00:34:08,441
Thank you, President Carviello.

300
00:34:08,461 --> 00:34:11,863
I think we've heard from a number of councilors.

301
00:34:11,903 --> 00:34:21,989
It looks like there potentially is a vote to pass the first reading tonight, but as long as there's limited to site plan review projects or greater, obviously.

302
00:34:22,950 --> 00:34:26,112
Just plain devil's advocate, my question would be to the solicitor is

303
00:34:27,488 --> 00:34:35,454
Because I understand it if it has to do with a deck or expanding a home so you can have a couple more feet in your bedroom or a walk-in closet, whatever it might be.

304
00:34:35,834 --> 00:34:40,317
And those are the people that, obviously, we don't want to have to bear the burden of hundreds and hundreds of dollars.

305
00:34:40,898 --> 00:34:51,526
But what about a single-family home that the owner wants to turn it into a three-family and it's a two-family district or it's a single-family district?

306
00:34:51,586 --> 00:34:55,709
Now, I'm playing devil's advocate because if that was in my neighborhood and it was down the street,

307
00:34:56,149 --> 00:35:01,953
in a single-family district and a homeowner wanted to put up a three-family, I'd want to know.

308
00:35:02,413 --> 00:35:02,594
Right.

309
00:35:02,694 --> 00:35:05,355
And I don't think necessarily that you're playing devil's advocate.

310
00:35:05,596 --> 00:35:08,257
What you're doing is drawing the line at a different place.

311
00:35:08,938 --> 00:35:09,078
Right.

312
00:35:09,458 --> 00:35:09,658
Right.

313
00:35:10,179 --> 00:35:11,600
And how could we do that?

314
00:35:12,920 --> 00:35:20,707
Well, I think that the best thing is to let the planning board have some people in to hear their opinions so they can make appropriate recommendations back to the council.

315
00:35:21,228 --> 00:35:37,603
So because while the line suggested tonight by a prospective amendment has been projects that would require site plan review, and you just pointed out a larger project than a small addition to a house that nonetheless may impact a particular neighborhood,

316
00:35:38,023 --> 00:35:40,465
That is drawing the line at a different place.

317
00:35:40,885 --> 00:35:50,792
And I think the best way to decide where to draw that line, and I don't say that either one of those ideas are wrong, even the initial idea is not wrong, it's a matter of judgment and choice.

318
00:35:51,332 --> 00:35:53,294
So the question is where is that line drawn?

319
00:35:53,314 --> 00:35:59,158
And that really is something that would be interesting to receive in the recommendation from the planning board.

320
00:35:59,758 --> 00:36:01,860
So I understand your point, Counselor.

321
00:36:01,920 --> 00:36:04,962
I think you're drawing the boundary line in a little different place.

322
00:36:05,242 --> 00:36:06,123
There's nothing wrong with that.

323
00:36:09,501 --> 00:36:09,821
Thank you.

324
00:36:11,442 --> 00:36:12,102
Vice President Mox.

325
00:36:12,643 --> 00:36:13,583
Thank you, Mr. President.

326
00:36:15,524 --> 00:36:34,834
Mr. Solicitor, in the letter dated November 8th regarding this paper 17-731, your response to the mayor on page 2, the last paragraph, it states that failure to comply with the ordinance requirements would not invalidate the approval of a variance.

327
00:36:34,994 --> 00:36:35,515
That's correct.

328
00:36:36,335 --> 00:36:54,620
And my question to you would be, if this was not implemented and the Zoning Board of Appeals did not comply with the state statute, would that be, in and of itself, a reason to invalidate approval of a variance?

329
00:36:54,941 --> 00:36:59,822
Not complying with the state statute would absolutely be a reason to invalidate something.

330
00:37:00,082 --> 00:37:01,043
That's happened before.

331
00:37:01,764 --> 00:37:10,112
We had years ago, there was a clerk of the ZBA who was ill with cancer and certain notices didn't go out.

332
00:37:10,653 --> 00:37:15,258
That case was in the land court for one day and came back for re-notification.

333
00:37:17,340 --> 00:37:34,076
So based on that, I guess my question is that, other than the fact that we're going to create a city ordinance, what would bound the Zoning Board of Appeals to follow it?

334
00:37:35,339 --> 00:37:42,444
If there's no ramification on whether or not they follow it, it doesn't impact an appeal.

335
00:37:44,185 --> 00:37:50,750
As you mentioned, it's governed by state statutory requirements or regulations.

336
00:37:51,679 --> 00:37:57,286
So what would bound them to follow this new notification of 400 feet?

337
00:37:57,846 --> 00:38:09,901
All municipal employees, and that includes board and commission members, are required to comply with the requirements set forth in the revised ordinances of the City of Medford.

338
00:38:10,321 --> 00:38:11,122
If they do not,

339
00:38:13,203 --> 00:38:14,164
what could happen to them.

340
00:38:14,664 --> 00:38:18,465
I really don't know, not being the person that appoints them, what could happen.

341
00:38:18,885 --> 00:38:28,988
But I'll tell you this, if a board or commission member just summarily said, well we're not doing that, we don't really care what the ordinance says, we have a fundamental problem that would have to be addressed.

342
00:38:29,388 --> 00:38:32,128
And it wouldn't be addressed by way of another ordinance.

343
00:38:32,448 --> 00:38:34,349
I think it would be addressed by way of removal.

344
00:38:36,472 --> 00:38:43,718
So you're saying once this is implemented, then we can rest assured that notification will take place based on whatever the ordinance reads?

345
00:38:44,058 --> 00:38:51,784
Yes, the words that you used, rest assured, sounds like, could I say that once the ordinance is in place that it will always be complied with?

346
00:38:52,184 --> 00:38:58,689
There's always room for the frailty of human nature and error.

347
00:38:58,989 --> 00:39:03,413
I'm not saying that it's a foolproof system, but it certainly is greater than what exists right now.

348
00:39:04,153 --> 00:39:06,134
And it may or may not be implemented for us.

349
00:39:06,154 --> 00:39:21,137
The reason why I bring it up, Mr. Solicitor, is that one of the ZBA meetings, it was brought up by a member of this council during public participation, that we may be interested in expanding their notification by changing city ordinance.

350
00:39:21,798 --> 00:39:25,379
And one of the board members more or less said, do whatever you have to do.

351
00:39:25,399 --> 00:39:26,559
We're not going to follow it anyways.

352
00:39:28,039 --> 00:39:31,140
And that was my concern, Mr. Solicitor.

353
00:39:31,741 --> 00:39:50,768
And if it doesn't invalidate, to me, if it's a city ordinance, and I realize what you're saying about appeals and so forth, but if it's a city ordinance and our own Zoning Board of Appeals does not adhere to the notification process that's laid out, that should be enough to invalidate whatever variance they gave out.

354
00:39:52,564 --> 00:39:55,326
So to me, that should be enough.

355
00:39:56,827 --> 00:39:57,608
I get what you're saying.

356
00:39:57,628 --> 00:40:01,050
What you're saying is that the remedy should be invalidation of the variance.

357
00:40:01,411 --> 00:40:12,939
However, if the variance is given in compliance with the state law, the fact that the municipal law wasn't followed or the municipal ordinance wasn't followed would not, in and of itself, invalidate the approval.

358
00:40:13,079 --> 00:40:14,821
That's clear in what my opinion is.

359
00:40:15,361 --> 00:40:16,342
I will agree with you.

360
00:40:16,702 --> 00:40:21,649
that if a board or commission member just summarily says, I don't care what you say, we're not doing it.

361
00:40:22,030 --> 00:40:32,184
That raises another issue which I think has to be remedied in a different way than invalidating an approval that's consistent with state law.

362
00:40:34,333 --> 00:40:43,782
If it's consistent with state law and somebody thumbed their nose at you, but it's consistent with state law, I think the remedy is not to invalidate the approval.

363
00:40:44,102 --> 00:40:46,744
The remedy is something else, which I think is removal.

364
00:40:47,545 --> 00:40:50,948
Of course, that's just my opinion.

365
00:40:51,749 --> 00:40:52,790
We appreciate your opinion.

366
00:40:56,421 --> 00:41:02,764
like what Councilor Falco threw out there by trying to target site plan review for units over six.

367
00:41:03,485 --> 00:41:17,852
On the other side, I can see, as Councilor Longo-Kurd mentioned, that a lot of the projects we're going through now are in commercial zoned areas and so forth, but as we're seeing development, we're seeing it in neighborhoods.

368
00:41:18,732 --> 00:41:26,477
And the complaints that I'm also receiving aren't just on main roads or in commercial industrial areas, they're in neighborhoods.

369
00:41:27,157 --> 00:41:34,881
And I, too, would like to see maybe some discussion and that may be for a future or the

370
00:41:36,582 --> 00:41:59,215
the zoning board itself, when they have their public hearing, to look at how do we rest assure that we don't target, naturally, someone that wants to put another foot onto their porch in their backyard, but target units that will have an impact, as the city solicitor mentioned, regarding traffic, regarding quality of life, regarding, you know,

371
00:42:00,435 --> 00:42:09,582
A lot of other issues, infrastructure, water pressure, and a host of other issues that usually come when you develop large projects.

372
00:42:09,602 --> 00:42:18,568
So I too would like to see a compromise on that and possibly lower the number of units and not just site plan review.

373
00:42:21,009 --> 00:42:21,910
Councilor Knight.

374
00:42:21,950 --> 00:42:22,771
Thank you, Mr. President.

375
00:42:22,811 --> 00:42:24,612
Councilor Rumley, this question is also for you.

376
00:42:28,493 --> 00:42:49,552
If an applicant is in substantial compliance with the state law but fails to comply with the local expanded ordinance and submits their application in compliance with one but not the other, does the clock start ticking on the Zoning Board of Appeals timelines relative to when they have to take the application up for hearing?

377
00:42:50,233 --> 00:42:55,497
The statutory timeframes are not waivable or changeable locally.

378
00:42:56,078 --> 00:42:59,541
There are timeframes during which times the Board of Appeals must act.

379
00:42:59,601 --> 00:43:02,243
If they do not, then there is constructive approval.

380
00:43:02,903 --> 00:43:07,287
I can tell you, having been down the road on a couple of constructive approval cases over the years,

381
00:43:08,507 --> 00:43:11,788
It's a very steep way to try to get an approval.

382
00:43:12,248 --> 00:43:20,690
Because what happens is, if somebody says the Board of Appeals didn't act within a certain time frame, and then they go for their building permit, you might say, well, everything's okay, right?

383
00:43:21,110 --> 00:43:24,371
Well, the building department is going to say, is this okay?

384
00:43:24,411 --> 00:43:28,612
So then they come to me, we look at the time frames, whether or not everything is the way it's supposed to be.

385
00:43:29,112 --> 00:43:35,454
But the litmus test on something like that is the lender who's lending to the person that's developing, in this case.

386
00:43:35,894 --> 00:43:41,827
The lender might say, I don't know if I want a loan on this project because you got a constructive approval from the ZBA.

387
00:43:42,167 --> 00:43:44,833
There are all kinds of variables when that stuff happens.

388
00:43:45,093 --> 00:43:45,574
All kinds.

389
00:43:49,220 --> 00:43:56,547
So if they put the application in and only just notify abutters of abutters within 300 feet, the time frame starts ticking right away.

390
00:43:56,988 --> 00:44:02,493
And the zoning board has no recourse to require them to expand the notification to the city ordinance.

391
00:44:02,593 --> 00:44:07,338
Well, we're hoping that the board is going to request their clerk to make sure that that's implied with, yes.

392
00:44:15,773 --> 00:44:20,057
So through the clerk, what does our next step have to be?

393
00:44:20,097 --> 00:44:22,459
Can we take a first reading or if we even got there?

394
00:44:22,499 --> 00:44:28,064
This is a zoning matter.

395
00:44:28,084 --> 00:44:33,790
It has to be referred to the Community Development Board for their recommendation and public hearing.

396
00:44:34,711 --> 00:44:36,552
Then it comes back if you accept

397
00:44:37,413 --> 00:44:44,497
the recommendations, then you would vote to go out to public hearing.

398
00:44:44,558 --> 00:44:46,799
Which is a two week process, two or three week process.

399
