01:58:27,731 --> 01:58:28,792
Let's look forward to 2018.

1274
01:58:29,512 --> 01:58:34,397
OK, let's jump from the business pages to the sports pages, or maybe this is sort of society pages.

1275
01:58:34,437 --> 01:58:36,900
I'm not quite sure whether they have those in Indian papers.

1276
01:58:36,940 --> 01:58:41,425
But when the Indian cricket captain gets married, it's national news.

1277
01:58:42,626 --> 01:58:42,926
It is.

1278
01:58:43,006 --> 01:58:44,848
And look, you know, weddings are a business here.

1279
01:58:44,868 --> 01:58:48,091
They're one of the big businesses, one of the things of the recession.

1280
01:58:49,165 --> 01:58:51,486
proof get bigger and bigger every year.

1281
01:58:51,606 --> 01:58:58,569
And Indians, it's, you know, Bisanyan prizes, weddings and the other things, the topic of conversation at this particular point of time.

1282
01:58:58,969 --> 01:59:06,212
And the marriage of Virat Kohli to Anushka Sharma, you know, this big Bollywood star marrying a big cricket star, has really grabbed the attention.

1283
01:59:06,252 --> 01:59:10,854
It's taken some of the conversation about what's happening in the economy and people just looking at that, really.

1284
01:59:10,874 --> 01:59:12,795
And I think it shows you the obsessions

1285
01:59:13,335 --> 01:59:14,656
that people have with weddings.

1286
01:59:14,696 --> 01:59:16,336
I mean, they had a secret wedding in Italy.

1287
01:59:17,357 --> 01:59:19,197
There was rumors that they were flying off there.

1288
01:59:19,217 --> 01:59:21,698
Then the whole country moved into a spin of weather.

1289
01:59:21,998 --> 01:59:25,980
India's most famous couple were about to finally tie the knot.

1290
01:59:26,000 --> 01:59:26,820
They have done so.

1291
01:59:27,181 --> 01:59:29,601
So you'd think that that means that the talking is going to stop.

1292
01:59:29,621 --> 01:59:30,682
That's the end of the story.

1293
01:59:30,722 --> 01:59:33,383
But every day, it's still going on and on and on.

1294
01:59:33,703 --> 01:59:35,764
what she wore, what the priest did.

1295
01:59:35,784 --> 01:59:39,986
I mean, everybody now wants to wear what Virat Kohli was wearing, what she was wearing.

1296
01:59:40,687 --> 01:59:44,609
Yeah, so weddings, big, big business, big topics of conversation here.

1297
01:59:44,849 --> 01:59:46,029
Come on, let's get over it.

1298
01:59:46,049 --> 01:59:47,850
Let's move on to something else now, India.

1299
01:59:48,070 --> 01:59:49,411
Got to be better stuff to talk about.

1300
01:59:49,751 --> 01:59:50,711
Rahul, thanks a lot.

1301
01:59:51,031 --> 01:59:52,832
Rahul Tandon this morning in Kolkata.

1302
01:59:53,592 --> 01:59:56,012
Now, didn't think I'd talk about this on Business Matters.

1303
01:59:56,273 --> 01:59:56,913
Peppa Pig.

1304
01:59:57,233 --> 01:59:58,313
Blamed for a lot of things.

1305
01:59:58,633 --> 02:00:03,354
Having a temper, encouraging children to be naughty, fat shaming daddy pig.

1306
02:00:03,854 --> 02:00:04,214
Shocking.

1307
02:00:04,815 --> 02:00:19,418
And it seems the cartoon character avidly watched by millions of children around the world is causing trouble again because a doctor here in Britain is blaming Peppa Pig for giving people unrealistic expectations of their medical practitioners, Terry Egan reports.

1308
02:00:20,018 --> 02:00:26,704
Dr. Brown-Bear, a GP who works alone and also appears to provide his patients with an excellent service.

1309
02:00:26,724 --> 02:00:35,851
His prompt offers direct telephone access, continuity of care, extended hours and is always ready for a home visit.

1310
02:00:35,951 --> 02:00:37,152
Dr. Brown-Bear speaking.

1311
02:00:37,352 --> 02:00:39,794
Hello doctor, this is Madame Gazelle.

1312
02:00:40,274 --> 02:00:41,515
A child is ill.

1313
02:00:41,876 --> 02:00:44,698
Don't panic, I'll come straight away.

1314
02:00:47,747 --> 02:01:00,755
Dr Catherine Bell wondered about the potential impact Dr Brownbear's actions could have on patient behaviour and, with her tongue firmly in her cheek, has looked at a number of cases, going on to examine their implications.

1315
02:01:01,216 --> 02:01:06,999
In one instance, Dr Brownbear makes an urgent home visit to a three-year-old piglet with a facial rash.

1316
02:01:07,400 --> 02:01:13,784
He reassures the parents it's nothing serious and offers a dose of medicine, adding that it's likely to clear up quickly.

1317
02:01:14,324 --> 02:01:24,997
This case, suggests Dr Bell, is an example of unnecessary prescribing for a viral illness and encourages patients to attempt to access their GP inappropriately.

1318
02:01:27,026 --> 02:01:38,549
Peppa Pig is broadcast in more than 180 countries and writing in the BMJ, Dr Bell suggests that the way primary care is portrayed is likely to be influential to many people all over the world.

1319
02:01:39,029 --> 02:01:56,593
While Peppa Pig conveys many positive public health messages, such as encouraging healthy eating, exercise and road safety, she suspects that exposure to Peppa Pig and its portrayal of general practice raises patient expectation and encourages the inappropriate use of primary care services.

1320
02:01:57,453 --> 02:01:58,954
Terry Egan reporting.

1321
02:01:59,334 --> 02:02:05,975
Yes, the doctor rushing out to the house call reminded everybody of the 1950s.

1322
02:02:06,536 --> 02:02:08,216
Catherine, it seems a bit unfair, doesn't it?

1323
02:02:08,776 --> 02:02:23,260
You're trying to come up with an entertaining and slightly educational TV strip and suddenly everyone's holding you to account for, even somewhat tongue-in-cheek, as Dr Catherine Bell no doubt was, for making unrealistic demands.

1324
02:02:24,054 --> 02:02:37,748
I think you're right, it's a little bit unfair, but I do have to say that granted I'm the daughter of a doctor and my children are his grandchildren and it's not unusual for us to be calling him in the middle of the night for something like a rash on one of my kids' faces.

1325
02:02:38,108 --> 02:02:42,733
So maybe I inherently just expect efficiency when it comes to GP services.

1326
02:02:42,873 --> 02:02:46,397
But you're going to tell me that your dad was exactly like Dr. Brown Bear, surely?

1327
02:02:47,217 --> 02:02:49,578
I think Dr. Brown Bear is moral on my father, you know.

1328
02:02:50,698 --> 02:02:52,798
And the thing is, Alexander, from a U.S.

1329
02:02:52,838 --> 02:03:04,701
perspective, this is really interesting because this goes to the heart of things like Sesame Street, which have this early learning mission to explain from ABCs right through to cultural behavior.

1330
02:03:04,741 --> 02:03:07,842
Absolutely a fascinating thing to write and perform.

1331
02:03:08,613 --> 02:03:23,005
Yes, but as you can also imagine in the United States that trying to translate all of the issues around our healthcare market and, you know, why certain people have access to different things would be quite difficult in a children's show.

1332
02:03:23,086 --> 02:03:29,291
Yeah, so we were wondering where Dr. Brown Bear would get, would say, you know, visa or MasterCard?

1333
02:03:31,027 --> 02:03:39,295
Yeah, or when Dr. Brown Bear would actually be an employee of CVS or Walgreens or have a strange opinion about Obamacare.

1334
02:03:39,635 --> 02:03:41,777
Yeah, we don't take that insurance.

1335
02:03:41,797 --> 02:03:51,326
But Catherine, does this travel or do you think the translations into those multiple cultural contexts have to be equally sophisticated?

1336
02:03:52,415 --> 02:04:02,243
I think, you know, at the end of the day, I remember my little girl loved Madame Gazelle, who was a teacher, and wanted to become a school teacher, just like I'm sure many children look at, you know, Dr. Brown Bear and want to become doctors.

1337
02:04:02,664 --> 02:04:05,306
So I think maybe, I think we should just take it for what it is.

1338
02:04:05,366 --> 02:04:06,967
It's a children's cartoon.

1339
02:04:07,788 --> 02:04:09,489
They try and instill positive messages.

1340
02:04:09,549 --> 02:04:12,772
I don't think we should be digging around too much for negative connotations.

1341
02:04:12,972 --> 02:04:13,272
Okay.

1342
02:04:13,333 --> 02:04:14,354
The digging stops here.

1343
02:04:14,534 --> 02:04:19,400
Thank you very much both, Alexander Kaufman, New York, Katherine Young this morning in Hong Kong.

1344
02:04:19,420 --> 02:04:21,703
It's been a pleasure having you along for the last hour.

1345
02:04:22,064 --> 02:04:23,265
Thanks to you all for listening.

