1475
02:15:28,117 --> 02:15:33,262
And the polls in the last few weeks, of course, have put these two candidates absolutely neck and neck.

1476
02:15:33,302 --> 02:15:40,810
The Democrats have been working hard to get out the black vote in places such as Birmingham.

1477
02:15:41,150 --> 02:15:43,713
And the fear amongst Republicans, of course,

1478
02:15:44,594 --> 02:15:59,707
is that the conservative white voters who would normally vote en masse for Roy Moore might be tempted to stay at home in the light of the allegations against him, those lurid allegations of sexual misconduct.

1479
02:15:59,847 --> 02:16:07,935
Turnout could be the key here and the early indications are that it may well have been higher than expected, Jonathan.

1480
02:16:08,575 --> 02:16:17,844
Normally, a Senate race in the Deep South wouldn't even, well, certainly wouldn't get the amount of coverage that this one in Alabama is.

1481
02:16:17,924 --> 02:16:21,047
Remind us why this race is being so closely watched.

1482
02:16:21,988 --> 02:16:22,829
Well, you're absolutely right.

1483
02:16:22,849 --> 02:16:30,817
What's astonishing about all this is that a Republican victory in a state such as Alabama should have been a slam dunk for the Republicans.

1484
02:16:31,238 --> 02:16:32,459
Alabama hasn't elected

1485
02:16:32,959 --> 02:16:35,581
a Democrat to the Senate for 25 years.

1486
02:16:35,641 --> 02:16:42,224
But the allegations against Roy Moore have turned everything on its head, basically.

1487
02:16:42,544 --> 02:16:58,693
Senior Republicans have been divided over whether to support him and protect the Senate majority, that narrow Senate majority, or shun him because of the sexual misconduct allegations and what they could mean in next year's midterm elections.

1488
02:16:59,253 --> 02:17:01,875
President Trump, of course, has gone from

1489
02:17:02,395 --> 02:17:24,995
tepid support from Roy Moore to more full-throttle support for him in recent days and a victory for Roy Moore would in a sense help establish President Trump's authority over a Senate that at times hasn't been completely compliant as far as he's concerned.

1490
02:17:25,475 --> 02:17:31,501
David Willis in Washington, D.C., watching the results come in from that key Senate race in Alabama.

1491
02:17:31,541 --> 02:17:39,468
We'll have more as we get it on whether we can draw any conclusions at this stage as to the possible result.

1492
02:17:40,228 --> 02:17:42,851
But for now, we will move on, but stay in the U.S.

1493
02:17:42,891 --> 02:17:47,895
because the Secretary of State there, Rex Tillerson, has urged North Korea to come to the negotiating table.

1494
02:17:48,015 --> 02:17:50,698
With tensions high over the country's nuclear program,

1495
02:17:51,198 --> 02:17:55,781
Speaking in Washington, Mr Tillerson said the countries could meet with no preconditions.

1496
02:17:56,601 --> 02:17:59,603
We're ready to talk anytime North Korea would like to talk.

1497
02:18:00,303 --> 02:18:03,365
And we're ready to have the first meeting without precondition.

1498
02:18:03,845 --> 02:18:04,566
Let's just meet.

1499
02:18:05,166 --> 02:18:06,527
We can talk about the weather if you want.

1500
02:18:06,547 --> 02:18:11,289
We can talk about whether it's going to be a square table or a round table if that's what you're excited about.

1501
02:18:11,830 --> 02:18:16,612
But can we at least sit down and see each other face to face?

1502
02:18:17,593 --> 02:18:19,614
And then we can begin to lay out

1503
02:18:20,396 --> 02:18:24,060
a road map of what we might be willing to work towards.

1504
02:18:24,421 --> 02:18:36,233
Well, previously, the US has demanded that North Korea disarm first, the White House saying that this is not a policy shift and that the president's views on North Korea have not changed.

1505
02:18:36,674 --> 02:18:42,160
Our correspondent at the US State Department, Barbara Pletusha, gave us her assessment of Mr Tillerson's speech.

1506
02:18:42,872 --> 02:18:44,433
He said, let's just meet and talk.

1507
02:18:44,494 --> 02:18:48,877
We just have to sit down face to face, get to know each other and put things on the table.

1508
02:18:48,898 --> 02:18:55,624
He said, it's not realistic to say that you can only talk about containing the nuclear program because, of course, Pyongyang is too invested in that.

1509
02:18:55,644 --> 02:19:00,548
So we need to, you know, see what they want to put on the table and whether we can discuss that.

1510
02:19:00,728 --> 02:19:03,391
But he said, ultimately, the U.S.

1511
02:19:03,491 --> 02:19:07,875
cannot accept a nuclear armed North Korea because it has a record of selling weaponry

1512
02:19:08,415 --> 02:19:11,238
And it doesn't abide by the rule of law, so it would just be too dangerous.

1513
02:19:11,359 --> 02:19:14,963
But still, it was quite a strong, I think, diplomatic offering to North Korea.

1514
02:19:15,343 --> 02:19:18,286
And how much of a policy shift is this by the US?

1515
02:19:18,326 --> 02:19:22,351
Because it's in stark contrast to a lot of the tough talk we've heard, certainly from the president.

1516
02:19:23,165 --> 02:19:29,868
Yes, the tough talk has contrasted with Mr. Tillerson's talk, but the policy, I think, has been the same, which is a diplomatic one that's been emphasized over and over again.

1517
02:19:29,949 --> 02:19:39,193
And Mr. Tillerson's approach has been to try to rally international support to isolate North Korea, and he says that there's been quite a lot of progress on that.

1518
02:19:39,253 --> 02:19:42,255
He said that sort of process was reaching a zenith, he said.

1519
02:19:42,635 --> 02:19:48,318
But in terms of offering talks without preconditions, he's never spelled out what the preconditions would be before

1520
02:19:48,938 --> 02:19:54,701
But I think it's probably a shift in that he's basically saying the US is ready for talks of any kind, at least to begin with.

1521
02:19:55,101 --> 02:19:57,183
It doesn't necessarily have to be about the nuclear program.

1522
02:19:57,603 --> 02:20:06,848
The thing that is the same, though, is that he spelled out that the goal was the same, and they've always been clear about the goal, which is that North Korea, in the end, would not be acceptable for it to have nuclear weapons.

1523
02:20:07,428 --> 02:20:11,450
Rex Tillerson and Donald Trump have had a little bit of a rocky relationship.

1524
02:20:11,510 --> 02:20:15,953
It wasn't all that long ago that there was talk of the Secretary of State being replaced.

1525
02:20:16,333 --> 02:20:18,334
Is his future certain at the moment?

1526
02:20:18,930 --> 02:20:24,974
Well, I don't think anything is certain, but certainly those reports were denied by Mr. Tillerson.

1527
02:20:25,014 --> 02:20:27,896
He said they were laughable previously to the press.

1528
02:20:27,936 --> 02:20:30,557
He said, you're always telling the wrong story, you need to get some new sources.

1529
02:20:30,597 --> 02:20:32,318
So he has previously dismissed them.

1530
02:20:32,619 --> 02:20:37,622
Mr. Trump has also, since those reports come out, has expressed some confidence in him.

1531
02:20:38,202 --> 02:20:46,826
I think there are tensions between the two that's been, I think, pretty widely reported, and they are quite different people, and they have different approaches to policy as well.

1532
02:20:46,886 --> 02:20:55,129
But certainly from the speech that Mr. Tillerson gave when he talked about everything he'd been working on in the year, and then he mentioned that he was planning to travel to South America in the new year.

1533
02:20:55,169 --> 02:20:56,530
We know he's planning to travel to Africa.

1534
02:20:57,115 --> 02:21:01,697
So he certainly sounded like a man who expected to continue in his job for at least a while longer.

1535
02:21:02,077 --> 02:21:02,978
Barbara Pletasha.

1536
02:21:03,598 --> 02:21:08,060
Now to a humanitarian crisis unfolding in the Democratic Republic of Congo.

1537
02:21:08,441 --> 02:21:14,624
The UN is warning that at least 400,000 children are suffering from severe acute malnutrition.

1538
02:21:15,164 --> 02:21:21,507
The crisis is at its worst in the central Kassai region where fighting erupted last year between local groups and government troops.

1539
02:21:22,227 --> 02:21:23,588
3,000 people have died.

1540
02:21:24,148 --> 02:21:27,710
Our Africa editor Fergal Keane travelled to Kassai and sent this report.

1541
02:21:29,831 --> 02:21:43,178
We're with a Pakistan Army patrol and we're moving along a dirt track outside the town of Chengulu and going in the direction of what we're told is a mass grave containing the bodies of people who were killed here.

1542
02:21:44,558 --> 02:21:46,519
We're just dismounting now from the vehicle.

1543
02:21:47,820 --> 02:21:48,560
It's somewhere near here.

1544
02:21:53,697 --> 02:21:57,281
Walking along a narrow track, which is largely overgrown.

1545
02:21:57,321 --> 02:22:00,205
There's high grass and different kinds of bushes all around me.

1546
02:22:01,386 --> 02:22:05,771
And down here at the end, I'm told, is a mass grave.

1547
02:22:06,692 --> 02:22:10,617
Nobody knows exactly how many people are in it, but it's men, women, and children.

1548
02:22:11,479 --> 02:22:29,333
and they were dumped here by the military and have come to this small depression where you can see bush was cleared away, ground was dug up and there's human clothing here, man's trousers reaching out of the earth.

1549
02:22:30,720 --> 02:22:37,127
A local woman approached us to say her 12-year-old son had been killed, and she'd witnessed the army dumping bodies.

1550
02:22:43,453 --> 02:22:52,982
The violence began when long-simmering resentments exploded into rebellion after security forces killed a chief, Kamina Ansapo, who'd rebelled against the government.

1551
02:22:54,163 --> 02:22:59,028
The Kabila regime was trying to entrench its hold on an area known as an opposition stronghold.

1552
02:22:59,768 --> 02:23:04,633
The chief's followers struck back, killing all they regarded as collaborators of the state.

1553
02:23:05,413 --> 02:23:08,356
There were mass beheadings, schools and clinics were burned.

1554
02:23:10,643 --> 02:23:18,207
The government responded with pitiless violence, killing militiamen and turning its guns on civilians accused of supporting the rebels.

1555
02:23:19,127 --> 02:23:25,410
I spoke with numerous survivors of the violence carried out by the state and the Banamura militia, which it supports.

1556
02:23:26,911 --> 02:23:31,553
I've come to the Ebenezer Church on the outskirts of the town of Chicago.

1557
02:23:32,113 --> 02:23:36,335
When I say church, it's basically tin shack.

1558
02:23:37,106 --> 02:23:41,536
a large open-air tin shack, crowded with children.

1559
02:23:41,596 --> 02:23:46,908
I've never seen so many children in a displaced environment and that backs up the statistic.

1560
02:23:47,737 --> 02:23:56,624
Out of an estimated 1.5 million people who were displaced, over 800,000 of them were children.

1561
02:23:56,664 --> 02:23:59,226
I saw people with machetes, guns and clubs.

1562
02:23:59,806 --> 02:24:03,469
They were beheading people, cutting arms and legs, slashing bellies.

1563
02:24:04,189 --> 02:24:06,131
I had to climb over dead bodies to escape.

1564
02:24:06,911 --> 02:24:09,793
I had four children, but could escape with only one.

1565
02:24:10,474 --> 02:24:11,575
The other three were killed.

1566
02:24:12,275 --> 02:24:15,658
The women at the church managed to escape, but others were abducted.

1567
02:24:16,604 --> 02:24:22,352
I met a mother and her 15-year-old daughter who were taken by the Banimura militia to isolated farms.

1568
02:24:25,335 --> 02:24:29,601
We had left our village in April and were taken as slaves on the farm the same month.

1569
02:24:29,941 --> 02:24:33,947
It's difficult to count how many times I was raped because it was during so many months.

1570
02:24:35,340 --> 02:24:36,761
I did not know where my daughter was.

1571
02:24:37,582 --> 02:24:39,323
She was released after I escaped.

1572
02:24:40,284 --> 02:24:43,847
They told her, go now, for your mother has escaped and can get us arrested.

1573
02:24:44,828 --> 02:24:49,171
Only then, when she joined me in Chicapa, did I discover that she had been raped too.

1574
02:24:51,141 --> 02:25:04,186
The UN peacekeeping force is just under 20,000 troops, but is being cut by 3,000 under American pressure, and all at a time when violence across the Congo is mounting amid widening political instability.

1575
02:25:05,306 --> 02:25:14,830
In Kassai, where the dead are cast into rivers, into mass graves, there's no real peace to keep, only a daily effort to hold back the forces of chaos.

1576
02:25:15,984 --> 02:25:19,967
our Africa editor Fergal Keane in the Democratic Republic of Congo.

1577
02:25:20,228 --> 02:25:22,049
You're listening to the BBC World Service.

1578
02:25:22,309 --> 02:25:23,310
Neil has the headlines.

1579
02:25:24,211 --> 02:25:31,697
Vote counting is getting underway in Alabama after polls closed in a highly charged contest to choose a new US senator.

1580
02:25:32,517 --> 02:25:38,963
The US Secretary of State Rex Tillerson says America is ready to open talks with North Korea without preconditions.

1581
02:25:40,308 --> 02:25:46,515
The story now of a three-week-old baby girl in Britain who was born with her heart outside her body.

1582
02:25:47,076 --> 02:25:51,121
After three operations to place her heart back in her chest, she has survived.

1583
02:25:51,521 --> 02:25:56,668
Our medical correspondent Fergus Walsh met her family and doctors at the hospital in Leicester.

1584
02:25:59,930 --> 02:26:00,631
Good girl.

1585
02:26:01,432 --> 02:26:01,832
Yeah.

1586
02:26:02,433 --> 02:26:03,834
She's a beautiful girl.

1587
02:26:04,275 --> 02:26:09,020
Proud parents bending over the cot of their three-week-old daughter, Vanellope.

1588
02:26:09,580 --> 02:26:14,025
She was born with a very rare condition where the heart grows outside the chest.

1589
02:26:14,445 --> 02:26:16,788
Her chances of survival were put at less than 10%.

1590
02:26:18,029 --> 02:26:22,954
But mum, Naomi Findley, and dad, Dean Wilkins, say she's a fighter.

1591
02:26:23,334 --> 02:26:24,935
more strength than I could ever imagine.

1592
02:26:25,235 --> 02:26:26,815
She came out kicking and screaming.

1593
02:26:26,855 --> 02:26:29,816
And then she gave all the surgeons agro, didn't she?

1594
02:26:30,136 --> 02:26:31,857
It was a beautiful moment, wasn't it?

1595
02:26:32,057 --> 02:26:33,117
Absolutely beautiful.

1596
02:26:33,958 --> 02:26:40,340
If you saw when she was first born, to where she is now and what they've done, it's... It's beyond a miracle, isn't it?

1597
02:26:40,700 --> 02:26:45,261
Doctors at Leicester's Glenfield Hospital say Vanellope has defied the odds.

1598
02:26:45,741 --> 02:26:52,022
Consultant paediatric cardiologist Frances Bulock says her prospects have greatly improved.

1599
02:26:52,262 --> 02:26:56,523
You know, her heart is covered by skin, hopefully sealed away from the environment.

1600
02:26:57,203 --> 02:26:58,503
She's still on a breathing machine.

1601
02:26:58,703 --> 02:27:01,204
She's still got drains in to take fluid away.

1602
02:27:01,964 --> 02:27:03,704
She's got a long road ahead of her.

1603
02:27:03,744 --> 02:27:06,325
It's not done, but I think they're much better than they were.

1604
02:27:06,785 --> 02:27:11,990
Phenelope has no breastbone and will need more surgery to create one in years to come.

1605
02:27:12,490 --> 02:27:19,136
Doctors are considering using material from a 3D printer or something organic that would grow with her.

1606
02:27:20,077 --> 02:27:27,641
Fergus Walsh, the Great Red Spot on Jupiter is the biggest storm in the solar system and we've known about it for more than 150 years.

1607
02:27:27,741 --> 02:27:32,883
We also know that it's wider than the Earth with wind speeds up to 650 kilometres an hour.

1608
02:27:33,363 --> 02:27:39,146
Now NASA says its space probe DUNE has discovered more about the Great Red Spot.

1609
02:27:39,706 --> 02:27:46,990
Our correspondent Jonathan Amos is at the American Geophysical Union meeting in New Orleans where the agency has been presenting its findings.

1610
02:27:47,730 --> 02:27:53,634
We've been observing the Great Red Spot on Jupiter probably since the invention of the telescope.

1611
02:27:53,674 --> 02:27:59,939
Yes, we've got records 150 years back, but probably, you know, we've been seeing it for something like 400 years.

1612
02:28:00,239 --> 02:28:01,220
That's extraordinary.

1613
02:28:01,500 --> 02:28:05,223
If you think about hurricanes on Earth, they last, what, a couple of weeks?

1614
02:28:05,963 --> 02:28:08,785
And then you think how long the Great Red Spot has been going.

1615
02:28:08,965 --> 02:28:09,886
Now, why is that?

1616
02:28:09,966 --> 02:28:10,807
What drives it?

1617
02:28:11,187 --> 02:28:14,990
And that's one of the mission goals of Juno, is to try and understand it.

1618
02:28:15,590 --> 02:28:19,733
And one of the first things it had to find out was just how deep its roots are.

1619
02:28:20,234 --> 02:28:26,318
Was it a feature that was just at the surface of the planet, or did those roots go deep, deep down inside?

1620
02:28:26,359 --> 02:28:34,064
Well, we know the answer to that question, or partially the answer to that question, because Juno has this microwave radiometer that can sense heat

1621
02:28:35,225 --> 02:28:40,367
inside the planet, and it can see that the roots go down at least 350 kilometers.

1622
02:28:40,407 --> 02:28:43,548
Now, that may not be the bottom of the Great Red Spot.

1623
02:28:43,628 --> 02:28:57,433
It may go down further, and if it can do some gravity measurements over the coming months, then we may well find out that this storm extends, you know, over a thousand kilometers down inside the planet, which would be quite extraordinary.

1624
02:28:57,933 --> 02:29:08,259
Now, if you go back to the formation of the solar system four and a half billion years ago, it's almost certain that Jupiter was the first thing to form after the Sun, sort of sucked up everything else that was around.

1625
02:29:08,499 --> 02:29:17,785
If you took all of the other planets, the comets, the asteroids, all of the other bits of debris apart from the Sun, you could fit it all inside of Jupiter.

1626
02:29:18,285 --> 02:29:24,916
So unless you understand how Jupiter works, you don't really understand how the rest of the solar system works.

1627
02:29:25,196 --> 02:29:32,948
So in many ways, this is one of the most important missions that NASA has ever undertaken, to reveal the great secrets of this amazing world.

1628
02:29:33,449 --> 02:29:37,291
That's Jonathan Amos on new discoveries about Jupiter's great red spot.

1629
02:29:37,752 --> 02:29:43,796
It is two years since the Paris Climate Agreement was signed and the question now is how to pay for it.

1630
02:29:43,936 --> 02:29:47,938
Representatives from around 50 countries are meeting again in the French capital.

1631
02:29:48,298 --> 02:29:54,082
Major investors have vowed to move away from the fossil fuel industry to try to reduce global warming.

1632
02:29:54,302 --> 02:29:55,323
Roger Harabin reports.

1633
02:29:55,983 --> 02:30:04,529
It's governments which set policies for cutting greenhouse gas emissions, but it's typically business and financial institutions which make those policies happen.

1634
02:30:05,190 --> 02:30:10,634
In Paris, more than a thousand firms and financial bodies pledged themselves to a low-carbon economy.

1635
02:30:11,214 --> 02:30:18,199
The commitment from the World Bank was the most eye-catching, with its promise to stop funding exploration in oil and gas.

1636
02:30:18,920 --> 02:30:21,642
Its president, Jim Yong Kim, said the time was right.

1637
02:30:22,122 --> 02:30:29,588
We're now seeing that the price of solar has gone down so much, the cost and size of batteries has gone down so much.

1638
02:30:30,148 --> 02:30:44,510
that we think that energy needs can be provided by other means and the science of this is just changing so quickly that we want to get out ahead and we don't think that we need to be in the upstream oil and gas business anymore.

1639
02:30:45,051 --> 02:30:48,553
There was a big announcement, too, from the French insurance firm AXA.

1640
02:30:49,033 --> 02:30:58,639
It's going to quadruple its investment in green technologies, sell its shares in coal, and phase out insurance cover for new coal and oil sands projects.

1641
02:30:59,499 --> 02:31:08,264
Earlier, the oil giant Exxon announced that it would publish reports on the impact of climate change policies on its huge reserves of fossil fuels.

1642
02:31:08,844 --> 02:31:11,586
Some think these might look a liability in years to come.

1643
02:31:12,406 --> 02:31:16,348
After today's initiatives, though, came a reality check by environmentalists.

1644
02:31:16,968 --> 02:31:22,931
They said the pledges still weren't enough to save vulnerable communities from the effects of a heating climate.

1645
02:31:23,611 --> 02:31:25,852
You're listening to the Newsroom from the BBC World Service.

1646
02:31:25,932 --> 02:31:27,833
Neil has some other stories from our news desk.

1647
02:31:28,333 --> 02:31:37,537
In a high-profile court case in Egypt, a pop singer, Shaima Ahmed, has been jailed for two years for making a raunchy music video, Ellen Johnston reports.

1648
02:31:38,220 --> 02:31:42,762
The video that got Shaima into trouble featured her dancing in lingerie.

1649
02:31:43,062 --> 02:31:49,844
She flirted with a classroom full of young men and ate a banana in a sexually suggestive manner.

1650
02:31:50,424 --> 02:31:54,066
The video would have been regarded as racy anywhere in the world.

1651
02:31:54,626 --> 02:32:00,048
In socially conservative Egypt, it provoked indignation and a torrent of criticism.

1652
02:32:00,728 --> 02:32:03,391
Sheymer was charged with inciting debauchery.

1653
02:32:04,032 --> 02:32:12,803
She denied the allegation, but she apologised, and when she came to court, she cut a much more modest figure, appearing in a face veil.

1654
02:32:13,573 --> 02:32:18,596
New research indicates feathered dinosaurs were covered in ticks, just like animals today.

1655
02:32:18,676 --> 02:32:25,500
Parasites similar to modern ticks have been found inside pieces of amber from Myanmar dating back 99 million years.

1656
02:32:26,120 --> 02:32:30,763
And the co-founder of the global hairdressing chain Tony and Guy has died at the age of 75.

1657
02:32:31,203 --> 02:32:40,769
Giuseppe Tony Mascolo, an Italian, established the first of his salons in London in the 1960s with his younger brother, Gaetano, known as Guy.

1658
02:32:41,792 --> 02:32:42,313
Thank you, Neil.

1659
02:32:42,373 --> 02:32:46,978
Now, when it comes to navigating, bees, it seems, do not bumble.

1660
02:32:47,359 --> 02:32:49,041
To tell us more, here's Richard Hamilton.

1661
02:32:49,702 --> 02:33:00,355
It's known as the travelling salesman problem, a benchmark question in computer science that poses the question, given a list of cities and the distance between each pair of cities,

1662
02:33:00,935 --> 02:33:09,699
What is the shortest possible route the salesman needs to take in order to visit each city and then return to his original starting point?

1663
02:33:10,320 --> 02:33:17,803
The scientists gave the bees the travelling salesman problem, except they used flowers instead of cities, to see if they could solve it.

1664
02:33:18,363 --> 02:33:25,947
They tried to trick the bees by offering them shortcuts between individual flowers that increased the total distance they travelled.

1665
02:33:26,647 --> 02:33:29,669
At first the bumblebees fell for these tempting traps,

