03:09:39,401 --> 03:09:46,374
Mr. Feltman said he'd left with the door to a negotiated solution ajar and fervently hoped the door would now be wide open.

2073
03:09:50,561 --> 03:10:04,035
The United Nations Children's Fund UNICEF has warned that more than 400,000 severely malnourished children under the age of five in the Democratic Republic of Congo could die within months without emergency intervention.

2074
03:10:04,675 --> 03:10:13,624
UNICEF said the crisis unfolding in the region of Kasai was due to a combination of violence, mass displacement of families and slumping agricultural output.

2075
03:10:14,945 --> 03:10:21,831
A baby who was born with her heart outside her body has survived in what's thought to be a first in Britain.

2076
03:10:22,251 --> 03:10:30,958
The baby, Vanellope Wilkins, who is three weeks old, has undergone three operations to place her heart back in her chest, Fergus Walsh explains.

2077
03:10:31,578 --> 03:10:37,022
Vanellope was born with a very rare condition where the heart grows outside the chest.

2078
03:10:37,463 --> 03:10:43,827
In most cases, babies are stillborn and Vanellope was given a less than 10% chance of survival.

2079
03:10:44,348 --> 03:10:50,733
But after three operations, surgeons have succeeded in putting her heart back and covering it with skin.

2080
03:10:51,413 --> 03:10:56,679
Phenelope has no breastbone and will need more surgery to create one in years to come.

2081
03:10:57,240 --> 03:11:03,507
Doctors are considering using material from a 3D printer or something organic that would grow with her.

2082
03:11:04,544 --> 03:11:11,387
Scientists say the region around the North Pole shows no sign of returning to its once reliably frozen state.

2083
03:11:11,867 --> 03:11:13,548
The annual assessment by the U.S.

2084
03:11:13,588 --> 03:11:22,452
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration says the rapidly warming Arctic indicates that its environmental system had reached a new normal.

2085
03:11:22,793 --> 03:11:29,156
The report said the winter sea ice in March was the smallest extent on record and the rate of change was increasing.

2086
03:11:30,276 --> 03:11:38,927
The United Nations Secretary-General Antnio Guterres has said continued subsidies of fossil fuel amount to humanity investing in its own doom.

2087
03:11:39,347 --> 03:11:47,838
Mr. Guterres told more than 50 heads of state gathered at the One Planet Summit in Paris, we are in a war for the very existence of life on our planet.

2088
03:11:48,478 --> 03:11:49,199
BBC News.

2089
03:11:50,211 --> 03:11:54,452
Welcome to Hard Talk on the BBC World Service with me, Stephen Sacker.

2090
03:11:54,952 --> 03:12:00,074
My guest today belongs in an elite club which didn't exist a generation ago.

2091
03:12:00,294 --> 03:12:13,477
He is a celebrity chef with a portfolio of television work, books, a media profile, oh, and a string of restaurants, including one bearing his name that has two Michelin stars.

2092
03:12:14,117 --> 03:12:20,327
Marcus Waring began life bagging up potatoes for his father, who was a fruit and veg trader.

2093
03:12:20,747 --> 03:12:24,934
Now he cooks for an exclusive clientele, including the Queen.

2094
03:12:25,334 --> 03:12:28,940
His story reflects a fundamental change in British culture.

2095
03:12:29,340 --> 03:12:32,863
Fifty years ago, the country's cuisine was a laughingstock.

2096
03:12:33,263 --> 03:12:35,265
Stodgy, bland and flavourless.

2097
03:12:35,785 --> 03:12:40,289
Now, Brits watch endless cooking and baking shows on TV.

2098
03:12:40,669 --> 03:12:45,713
Chefs are lionised and the country seems fascinated by fancy food.

2099
03:12:46,173 --> 03:12:47,154
But is that healthy?

2100
03:12:47,635 --> 03:12:52,218
Or are there still some dodgy things going on in the British kitchen?

2101
03:12:52,679 --> 03:12:55,000
Well, Marcus Waring joins me now.

2102
03:12:55,221 --> 03:12:56,562
Welcome to Hard Talk.

2103
03:12:57,350 --> 03:13:06,035
There are an awful lot of chefs in the world, only a very few elite top chefs.

2104
03:13:06,155 --> 03:13:09,317
What distinguishes the very best from the rest?

2105
03:13:09,717 --> 03:13:11,558
I think, first of all, it's a mindset.

2106
03:13:12,218 --> 03:13:13,179
It's a work ethic.

2107
03:13:13,499 --> 03:13:23,825
And I think there is a type of sacrifice that a top chef has and wants to sort of drive themselves as an individual to excel.

2108
03:13:24,565 --> 03:13:25,945
head and shoulders above everybody else.

2109
03:13:26,526 --> 03:13:33,008
A lot of advice that I've ever had through the years coming through the ranks was, and it came from my father originally, was to stand out from the crowd.

2110
03:13:34,028 --> 03:13:35,669
And to do that, you need to do something different.

2111
03:13:35,689 --> 03:13:42,551
Most of the great chefs around the world started as apprentices to other truly great chefs.

2112
03:13:42,591 --> 03:13:45,852
And if we look at your CV, you work with Albert Roux.

2113
03:13:46,372 --> 03:13:49,153
You've obviously famously worked a lot with Gordon Ramsay.

2114
03:13:49,273 --> 03:13:52,074
They're both, in their different ways, great chefs.

2115
03:13:52,514 --> 03:13:55,876
So did you acquire skills and knowledge directly from them?

2116
03:13:56,556 --> 03:13:57,176
Oh, without a doubt.

2117
03:13:57,436 --> 03:14:01,978
Your travels, your working in kitchens is the foundation of who you are as a chef.

2118
03:14:02,458 --> 03:14:09,381
The most important thing about being a good chef, or trying to be a good chef, or someone who's going to be a little bit different, is working with some of the best chefs.

2119
03:14:09,901 --> 03:14:18,385
And when you work through all the different kitchens, you're inspired, you're energized, but you're also gathering knowledge, education, and discipline.

2120
03:14:18,845 --> 03:14:23,489
They're leaders of examples, and they're leaders of their industry, and they have something to offer.

2121
03:14:23,649 --> 03:14:25,411
They may not tell or talk to you every day.

2122
03:14:25,431 --> 03:14:34,358
They may not tell you an idea or recipe, but you have to go into their kitchens and feed off their energy, like a big battery that you're just sucking everything out of it.

2123
03:14:34,678 --> 03:14:36,279
You store it while you're training.

2124
03:14:36,620 --> 03:14:37,861
You go and train more.

2125
03:14:38,121 --> 03:14:39,042
You put it on the shelf.

2126
03:14:39,202 --> 03:14:40,403
You go and train in another kitchen.

2127
03:14:40,423 --> 03:14:41,744
You put all that information on the shelf.

2128
03:14:41,764 --> 03:14:46,508
And then when you become a head chef, you bring it all down, and you use all that experience.

2129
03:14:46,868 --> 03:14:54,275
I've got, as it happens, your menus from last night here at Marcus, your flagship two Michelin star restaurant.

2130
03:14:54,535 --> 03:14:58,398
And therefore, I'm looking at this, I mean, it all looks delicious.

2131
03:14:59,019 --> 03:15:12,131
I notice a very big emphasis on British produce, you know, from starters of wood pigeon and Portland crab and glazed ox tongue with Dorset snails through to your mains.

2132
03:15:13,131 --> 03:15:20,095
Herdwick lamb, one, Cumbrian rose veal neck, another, grouse, all of this very, sounds delicious, but very British.

2133
03:15:20,255 --> 03:15:20,456
Yes.

2134
03:15:20,536 --> 03:15:24,598
So what, you know, this who am I question, what are your menus saying about who you are?

2135
03:15:24,938 --> 03:15:32,903
So the way I look at my restaurants, and because the way in which industry has changed, and farming, and the way in which we receive our produce, I look at

2136
03:15:33,223 --> 03:15:37,346
the UK, the United Kingdom, as my local community of food.

2137
03:15:37,606 --> 03:15:41,769
Because I could put an order in this morning in Scotland and get it tomorrow morning.

2138
03:15:42,130 --> 03:15:44,251
Things move very quickly now around the country.

2139
03:15:44,551 --> 03:15:46,072
So local, United Kingdom.

2140
03:15:46,313 --> 03:15:53,378
Then I spread further afield into Europe for other different types of produce that are better, or farmed better, or just taste better.

2141
03:15:53,658 --> 03:15:55,840
And we're always searching for something really nice.

2142
03:15:55,860 --> 03:16:00,523
But I don't like to go too far across the world to gather food produce.

2143
03:16:00,623 --> 03:16:02,604
this idea of food miles matters to you?

2144
03:16:02,764 --> 03:16:03,265
Very much so.

2145
03:16:03,345 --> 03:16:09,589
I think now in the world we need to be very careful that we're not purchasing too much from all over the world.

2146
03:16:09,649 --> 03:16:12,471
I don't, you know, have Japanese flavors through my menu.

2147
03:16:12,551 --> 03:16:14,172
I don't have curries going through the menu.

2148
03:16:14,432 --> 03:16:20,136
There's certain things that I don't need to put in to this menu because it's not really a reflection of me as a person.

2149
03:16:20,476 --> 03:16:25,560
I've never trained in lots of different cuisines but I will never experiment them on my menu.

2150
03:16:25,840 --> 03:16:28,642
So the reflection of the menu and the ingredients that you've talked about

2151
03:16:29,162 --> 03:16:35,088
are about a local lad from the northwest of England using the produce of this fabulous country, this island that we live on.

2152
03:16:35,369 --> 03:16:35,709
I love it.

2153
03:16:35,729 --> 03:16:41,074
The phrase, a local lad from Southport, wasn't it, in the northwest of England with a dad who was a market trader.

2154
03:16:41,214 --> 03:16:42,215
It's a great story.

2155
03:16:43,216 --> 03:16:43,577
Does it

2156
03:16:44,137 --> 03:16:53,921
sit uneasily with you in any way, that here we are in the very poshest, most expensive part of London, and all this fabulous food you're serving, it comes at a price.

2157
03:16:54,482 --> 03:16:56,102
Your tasting menu is 120 or roughly $140.

2158
03:16:56,142 --> 03:16:57,443
Your a la carte, I imagine, a main would be 60, 70.

2159
03:16:57,523 --> 03:16:59,184
Just a bit less than that.

2160
03:17:04,546 --> 03:17:06,507
But these are big numbers.

2161
03:17:06,928 --> 03:17:08,769
This is out of the reach of most people.

2162
03:17:08,929 --> 03:17:11,470
For a local lad from Southport, does that bother you?

2163
03:17:12,491 --> 03:17:17,054
No, it doesn't bother me because I think it's not about all men being equal.

2164
03:17:17,474 --> 03:17:18,595
It's about a matter of choice.

2165
03:17:19,315 --> 03:17:21,256
And I think what we do offer is choice.

2166
03:17:21,476 --> 03:17:27,697
There are tasty menus, there are a la carte menus, but there are also very good, reasonable lunch menus.

2167
03:17:28,137 --> 03:17:29,677
The wine is if you're choosing.

2168
03:17:29,938 --> 03:17:36,739
You can come to this restaurant and spend the same amount of money on a glass of wine than you would in a good bar or a good pub.

2169
03:17:37,219 --> 03:17:38,339
It's all a point of choice.

2170
03:17:38,440 --> 03:17:44,381
So with the thousands of bottles that we have on our menu, when you come here, there is something for everybody.

2171
03:17:44,941 --> 03:17:48,542
So I don't look at it as this is a rich man's room or we're in Knightsbridge.

2172
03:17:49,542 --> 03:17:50,863
Anybody can come to my restaurant.

2173
03:17:51,083 --> 03:17:54,885
You can have some tap water, you can have a glass of house wine, and you can have a lunch menu.

2174
03:17:55,185 --> 03:17:58,987
And for two people, you could be out the door less than 100 pound, if that's how you wish.

2175
03:17:59,647 --> 03:18:03,809
But it's your choice to come and spend the value that you want to spend.

2176
03:18:04,249 --> 03:18:12,473
Isn't it nice, even from a northern lad, to maybe come with your girlfriend or your wife and dress up and come to Knightsbridge, come to London, do something different?

2177
03:18:12,813 --> 03:18:14,374
We're not on everyone's doorstep.

2178
03:18:14,394 --> 03:18:16,135
We just happen to be in the heart of London.

2179
03:18:16,595 --> 03:18:17,335
I sort of love it.

2180
03:18:18,276 --> 03:18:20,777
I'm proud to have worked my way from there.

2181
03:18:21,418 --> 03:18:23,479
It didn't arrive on a silver tray.

2182
03:18:24,059 --> 03:18:25,240
It was a lot of hard work.

2183
03:18:25,480 --> 03:18:26,900
And what about food snobbery?

2184
03:18:27,121 --> 03:18:28,761
I mean, you have two Michelin stars.

2185
03:18:28,781 --> 03:18:30,542
Not many chefs around the world do.

2186
03:18:32,043 --> 03:18:41,293
But there is something about this whole sort of fetishization of the Michelin star which sticks in some people's throats.

2187
03:18:41,373 --> 03:18:49,982
Do you sometimes feel that it's the wrong way to really judge the quality of food and restaurants?

2188
03:18:50,632 --> 03:18:51,132
No, I don't.

2189
03:18:51,673 --> 03:18:54,494
I think Michon are very, very important and very present.

2190
03:18:55,255 --> 03:19:00,858
I think their history determines how good they really are.

2191
03:19:01,498 --> 03:19:07,662
They are judging chefs as a guide and they're giving you a point of recognition and they're giving you an accolade.

2192
03:19:07,822 --> 03:19:09,003
It's not something you ask for.

2193
03:19:09,543 --> 03:19:13,385
it is given to you as almost a gift of your standards of what you do.

2194
03:19:13,445 --> 03:19:14,965
Yeah, but it puts you under enormous pressure.

2195
03:19:14,985 --> 03:19:25,089
I mean, some chefs have started saying to Michelin, even if they've had in the past one or two stars, they're now saying, I don't want to be part of your network.

2196
03:19:25,129 --> 03:19:26,630
I don't want to be judged by you anymore.

2197
03:19:26,670 --> 03:19:29,211
The pressure is too constant.

2198
03:19:29,331 --> 03:19:30,131
It's too immense.

2199
03:19:30,431 --> 03:19:35,353
The things you require of us in terms of the level of service, the presentation are just

2200
03:19:35,673 --> 03:19:38,796
actually making us a restaurant we don't want to be.

2201
03:19:39,217 --> 03:19:43,741
I completely disagree because I don't think it's the Michelin that are putting that pressure upon the chef.

2202
03:19:44,201 --> 03:19:47,685
It's the general public and the expectation of the general public.

2203
03:19:48,305 --> 03:19:52,029
In the last 10 years, social media has become a big part.

2204
03:19:52,530 --> 03:19:57,555
Everybody in your restaurants now can post their thoughts of the dinner, of the experience that they're eating.

2205
03:19:58,195 --> 03:19:59,917
So I think it's more than just me.

2206
03:20:00,017 --> 03:20:01,758
Every person at your table is now a reviewer.

2207
03:20:01,898 --> 03:20:02,238
Exactly.

2208
03:20:02,579 --> 03:20:03,840
They can post something on the internet.

2209
03:20:03,860 --> 03:20:04,901
Does that scare the hell out of you?

2210
03:20:05,021 --> 03:20:05,281
Oh, no.

2211
03:20:06,202 --> 03:20:06,342
No.

2212
03:20:06,602 --> 03:20:07,363
It's a challenge.

2213
03:20:07,803 --> 03:20:08,764
It sets standards.

2214
03:20:09,184 --> 03:20:11,966
It even tells me what my restaurant's doing when I'm not here.

2215
03:20:12,367 --> 03:20:14,508
You've got to embrace technology.

2216
03:20:14,548 --> 03:20:15,429
You have to embrace it.

2217
03:20:15,749 --> 03:20:18,632
Even if I don't like it and do it as well as the next chef.

2218
03:20:19,432 --> 03:20:23,155
I do have a team of people around me that can advise me and show me how to move forward.

2219
03:20:23,956 --> 03:20:31,301
But if I look down on that process and I look down and say Michelin delivers pressure, then I'd be a nervous wreck.

2220
03:20:31,401 --> 03:20:37,106
And you must always turn that pressure into positive thinking and positive energy and enjoy your job.

2221
03:20:37,626 --> 03:20:42,449
go back to your roots, think about those ingredients, stop worrying about what everyone's saying about you.

2222
03:20:42,669 --> 03:20:43,450
The late A.A.

2223
03:20:43,510 --> 03:20:55,197
Gill, I don't know if you knew him, but he was one of Britain's sort of best-known restaurant reviewers, and he rebelled against the Michelin spirit, the sort of smart, formal dining that it seemed to encourage.

2224
03:20:55,217 --> 03:21:00,480
He said this, he said, the guide appears to be wholly out of touch with the way that people now actually eat.

2225
03:21:01,220 --> 03:21:05,882
It's still rewarding, fat, conservative, fussy rooms.

2226
03:21:06,402 --> 03:21:17,125
Maybe he meant rooms like this, that use expensive ingredients with ingratiating pomp to serve glossy plutocrats.

2227
03:21:17,885 --> 03:21:18,966
Is that Marcus?

2228
03:21:19,386 --> 03:21:19,506
No.

2229
03:21:20,786 --> 03:21:21,926
Absolutely not.

2230
03:21:22,226 --> 03:21:24,367
And I don't think fine dining is that.

2231
03:21:24,887 --> 03:21:34,989
I think there are a lot of our food writers and our critics, maybe, that don't see the fun or the luxury or the enjoyment in fine dining because it is a homage to the chef.

2232
03:21:35,229 --> 03:21:37,210
And I think that the world has changed.

2233
03:21:37,270 --> 03:21:48,873
And I think a chef cooking in a high street restaurant that's got 20 seats in and he's slaving away in the back of the kitchen with an open kitchen, that is as enjoyable in today's world as eating in a fine dining restaurant.

2234
03:21:49,013 --> 03:21:49,893
It's all about what

2235
03:21:50,853 --> 03:21:52,494
somebody wants from an occasion.

2236
03:21:53,154 --> 03:21:56,776
And if I'm going to set up restaurants in this hotel, it's a five-star hotel.

2237
03:21:56,876 --> 03:21:58,076
It is known all over the world.

2238
03:21:58,096 --> 03:22:01,618
There's a level of luxury that I have to provide and I want to provide.

2239
03:22:01,858 --> 03:22:08,460
It strikes me that as you've become more successful, like so many, many top chefs, you've developed the brand.

2240
03:22:08,500 --> 03:22:10,261
You've become a TV personality.

2241
03:22:10,281 --> 03:22:14,343
You're on the British MasterChef show, which has made you enormously popular in this country.

2242
03:22:14,643 --> 03:22:17,324
You also have opened other restaurants in central London.

2243
03:22:17,404 --> 03:22:19,145
So now you've got a stable of three.

2244
03:22:19,785 --> 03:22:30,468
It all means that you are not every single lunchtime and dinner actually in the kitchen here at your number one restaurant doing it yourself.

2245
03:22:31,008 --> 03:22:41,912
Now it strikes me that when people come here and they, as we've discussed, do pay a substantial amount of money for food from the Marcus restaurant, they expect Marcus Waring to be slaving away in the kitchen.

2246
03:22:42,052 --> 03:22:42,912
I think life has changed.

2247
03:22:43,632 --> 03:22:49,559
And up until four years ago, when I revamped this restaurant, I was in this kitchen every single day.

2248
03:22:50,720 --> 03:22:52,882
I never looked for television.

2249
03:22:53,183 --> 03:22:54,224
It came and found me.

2250
03:22:54,644 --> 03:22:56,987
I never, ever woke up and wanted to write a cookery book.

2251
03:22:57,427 --> 03:23:01,111
And I never, ever wanted or needed to open two other restaurants on top of this.

2252
03:23:01,131 --> 03:23:02,553
I was very satisfied with what I had.

2253
03:23:02,573 --> 03:23:03,314
So why did you do it?

2254
03:23:03,594 --> 03:23:04,675
Why did you stretch yourself?

2255
03:23:04,755 --> 03:23:10,617
Because I found that I had some very talented people underneath me that I had to find opportunities for.

2256
03:23:10,897 --> 03:23:20,220
And what I see is, having those other restaurants and coming out of the restaurant, I've created opportunities for very talented people to become bosses within their own right, within my stable.

2257
03:23:20,260 --> 03:23:22,361
But what if you stretch yourself too thin?

2258
03:23:22,721 --> 03:23:28,063
What if the standards at this restaurant, to be honest, are not quite as good when you're not here?

2259
03:23:28,243 --> 03:23:28,643
I come back.

2260
03:23:29,483 --> 03:23:34,867
I say goodbye to television, I say goodbye to books, and I do the job that I'm paid to do, which is cook.

2261
03:23:35,327 --> 03:23:38,309
The rest is just purely a luxury item that is added onto my life.

2262
03:23:38,750 --> 03:23:40,091
Interesting you talk about the team.

2263
03:23:40,291 --> 03:23:56,082
There has been a lot of discussion recently about the workplace temperature in top kitchens, and there is a lot of discussion about, and there's no other word for it, bullying and abuse that happens in kitchens and is often driven

2264
03:23:57,423 --> 03:24:03,649
by the character of the number one chef, which in this case, of course, would be you.

2265
03:24:03,709 --> 03:24:05,931
Have you bullied your staff in the past?

2266
03:24:06,111 --> 03:24:09,574
I think bullying is a word that is dressed up in many different ways.

2267
03:24:10,115 --> 03:24:12,977
I was born in the 70s and bullying was something that was done in a playground.

2268
03:24:13,178 --> 03:24:15,780
It was a fight, it was a push, it was verbal.

2269
03:24:15,960 --> 03:24:18,082
I don't think that happens in kitchens.

2270
03:24:18,302 --> 03:24:20,765
I've never experienced it myself in kitchens.

2271
03:24:21,285 --> 03:24:33,757
raise my voice, raise my voice, swear, shout and drive people very very hard through hard service, yes I've had it done to me and I have done it to my staff in the past.

2272
03:24:33,817 --> 03:24:44,507
There have been serious incidents in kitchens, I'm just looking at an incident in France where a station chef deliberately and repeatedly scolded his kitchen assistant

2273
03:24:44,987 --> 03:25:01,995
There were other incidents that came into light after that, with sous-chefs and assistants recounting tales of abuse ranging, and I'm quoting here from a slap, sounds absurd, but it's not, a slap in the face with a wet fish, being stabbed in the calves with a kitchen knife, all sorts of different burning incidents.

2274
03:25:02,555 --> 03:25:11,219
One ex-kitchen assistant told a report into this in France, because they took it very seriously, he said, quote, these torturers must be told that they are destroying lives.

2275
03:25:11,679 --> 03:25:13,540
What the heck is going on in some of these kitchens?

2276
03:25:13,660 --> 03:25:22,005
I think these are very few instances that are overshadowing a fabulous industry that's bigger than a handful of incidents or many, many more.

2277
03:25:22,365 --> 03:25:28,369
There are millions of people working in our industry and there are thousands and thousands of kitchens just running through London alone.

2278
03:25:28,869 --> 03:25:30,670
I think the kitchens are pressure cookers.

2279
03:25:31,370 --> 03:25:35,973
What has changed, and this is something we really must focus on, is that the kitchens have become very much open places now.

2280
03:25:36,413 --> 03:25:39,635
and the chef is very much part of the front of service as well as the back.

2281
03:25:39,735 --> 03:25:40,976
Chefs are now delivering food.

2282
03:25:41,297 --> 03:25:53,805
So I believe that the way in which we've changed... You actually come out here of an evening and... We can come out, any of my chefs can come out here and speak to customers, but what's changed is we the chef have now neutralised error in kitchen.

2283
03:25:54,225 --> 03:25:55,967
The pressure cooker of a kitchen was driven by

2284
03:25:56,867 --> 03:26:12,694
Hard cookery on top of a hot stove and inside the oven it was all cooked last minute So the science of food has allowed us to change the way in which we cook So we're actually taking sometimes the training out of our young chefs to actually make the job easier Because there's so much choice

2285
03:26:13,314 --> 03:26:16,698
and there's so few people wanting to necessarily work in our industry.

2286
03:26:16,738 --> 03:26:18,480
Maybe that's because you don't pay them enough as well.

2287
03:26:18,540 --> 03:26:18,900
That's wrong.

2288
03:26:19,220 --> 03:26:20,161
We do pay them very well.

2289
03:26:20,181 --> 03:26:22,644
We pay our staff minimum and above the minimum wage.

2290
03:26:22,824 --> 03:26:27,709
But that seems a bit, you know, minimum wage is a bit of a low bar you're setting yourself.

2291
03:26:27,789 --> 03:26:33,355
Minimum wage though is a point of if you work an eight-hour day you're going to find it tough to survive.

2292
03:26:33,875 --> 03:26:43,423
You know, some of my chefs in the kitchen do much, much longer days and can earn anything up to 25,000, 30,000 and be a commie chef, which is practically just above about being a trainee chef.

2293
03:26:43,863 --> 03:26:49,708
Yes, they'll put in a few... But the average wage in the UK is 27,000.

2294
03:26:50,288 --> 03:26:56,093
You're saying if they work ridiculously long hours, your guys might just get to that sort of threshold.

2295
03:26:56,833 --> 03:26:59,535
And yet you're one of the most luxurious restaurants in all of London.

2296
03:26:59,916 --> 03:27:02,618
But then we are also delivering a standard.

2297
03:27:02,938 --> 03:27:05,280
This is a school of education as well as a job.

2298
03:27:05,620 --> 03:27:10,964
And I think the difference, and we must identify this, is that you do not come into fine dining just for a job.

2299
03:27:11,304 --> 03:27:12,746
You have to want to be here.

2300
03:27:12,986 --> 03:27:14,267
The key thing here is choice.

2301
03:27:14,967 --> 03:27:17,869
And everybody that wakes up in the morning in this part of the Western world

2302
03:27:18,730 --> 03:27:19,911
can have a choice in life.

2303
03:27:19,951 --> 03:27:22,552
You can either get out of bed and go and look for a job.

2304
03:27:23,072 --> 03:27:27,694
You can work as many hours as you like and you can pretty much never ever be out of work.

2305
03:27:28,414 --> 03:27:33,756
But don't work in fine, fine dining at the top end if you want an easy life because it doesn't exist.

2306
03:27:34,276 --> 03:27:40,719
Brits, British people, spend three billion pounds a year on ready meals.

2307
03:27:41,139 --> 03:27:43,600
Now that's six times more than in Spain.

2308
03:27:45,100 --> 03:27:51,842
We still, whatever we do, when we switch the telly on and watch you cooking up fine food, we then go to the shop and buy a ready meal.

2309
03:27:52,142 --> 03:27:54,342
We're buying ready meals for one reason and one reason only.

2310
03:27:54,503 --> 03:28:02,444
They're there sitting on the shelves already available, there's more of them, and people are working harder and have less time and maybe don't want to cook when they get home.

2311
03:28:03,125 --> 03:28:05,405
School's finished later, the school runs different.

2312
03:28:05,805 --> 03:28:12,387
Everybody's lifestyle is changing, social media is changing everything, but if you want to look at food, go to supermarkets,

2313
03:28:12,707 --> 03:28:14,188
There's your problem of obesity.

2314
03:28:14,228 --> 03:28:15,629
There's your problem of convenience.

2315
03:28:15,869 --> 03:28:24,936
It's interesting to me that you talk about the obesity problem and you say that you believe you're part of a culture which is beginning to respect and understand food much better.

2316
03:28:25,497 --> 03:28:33,283
But you actually opposed your fellow top chef Jamie Oliver when he campaigned so long and hard

2317
03:28:33,843 --> 03:28:45,128
For a sugar tax to be put on, for example, the sugary drinks, the pop that so many kids still consume, you seem to think that was a very bad idea.

2318
03:28:45,228 --> 03:28:45,568
Why?

2319
03:28:45,848 --> 03:28:47,669
I don't think it was a bad idea.

2320
03:28:47,949 --> 03:28:49,870
My concern is what happens to that tax.

2321
03:28:50,510 --> 03:28:56,833
I think what Jamie Oliver has done over the years has really opened a lot of people up to how we cook at home.

2322
03:28:57,374 --> 03:28:59,475
And he's made people aware of lots of different things.

2323
03:28:59,515 --> 03:29:01,816
He's the one that put all the petitions together.

2324
03:29:01,856 --> 03:29:06,999
He's the guy that went to Downing Street and made a campaign for better quality school lunches for kids.

2325
03:29:07,059 --> 03:29:11,541
You can't just stop at the door of Downing Street, get the tax on there and then maybe just stop.

2326
03:29:11,661 --> 03:29:13,302
But his point about the tax isn't so much

2327
03:29:14,042 --> 03:29:22,889
What we do with the tax money is to send a price signal to people that they shouldn't be buying all these very sweetened fizzy drinks.

2328
03:29:22,969 --> 03:29:26,091
And if the price goes up a little bit, hopefully... They'll still buy them.

2329
03:29:26,111 --> 03:29:26,851
Do you think they will?

2330
03:29:26,911 --> 03:29:27,071
Yes.

2331
03:29:27,572 --> 03:29:29,453
Alcohol will go up in a bubble.

2332
03:29:29,473 --> 03:29:37,559
But you see, if I may say so, you seem to have a view that government and the authorities have no role to play in changing people's habits.

2333
03:29:37,599 --> 03:29:39,040
You said this not so long ago, you said

2334
03:29:39,520 --> 03:29:41,883
It's not the responsibility of government, but of parents.

2335
03:29:41,923 --> 03:29:43,004
We're all human beings.

2336
03:29:43,024 --> 03:29:44,126
We can all read and write.

2337
03:29:44,166 --> 03:29:45,567
Let's not blame the government.

2338
03:29:45,588 --> 03:29:48,631
There are only two people to blame for the obesity crisis.

2339
03:29:49,172 --> 03:29:50,053
Mum and Dad.

2340
03:29:50,253 --> 03:29:51,615
Yeah, but doesn't it start at home?

2341
03:29:51,935 --> 03:29:54,939
Why should the government be responsible for what people purchase in a shop?

2342
03:29:55,319 --> 03:29:57,422
Why should we hold the government responsible?

2343
03:29:58,222 --> 03:29:59,243
for our choices.

2344
03:29:59,683 --> 03:30:05,488
They're not our teachers, they're not our guardians, they do a completely different role and a hard role at that.

2345
03:30:05,548 --> 03:30:12,793
And quite honestly, I think they've got more important things to worry about with the economy and with Brexit and what they're going to do with our taxes.

2346
03:30:13,153 --> 03:30:16,134
than worry about what we are consuming at home.

2347
03:30:16,734 --> 03:30:19,435
Is Brexit worrying you as a restaurateur?

2348
03:30:19,475 --> 03:30:21,216
Is it going to change your business?

2349
03:30:21,716 --> 03:30:23,377
Yes, on many ways.

2350
03:30:23,617 --> 03:30:25,117
I voted to remain.

2351
03:30:25,518 --> 03:30:29,019
I've learned more about Brexit since we voted to leave Europe.

2352
03:30:29,419 --> 03:30:30,719
I wish it had been the other way around.

2353
03:30:30,900 --> 03:30:33,921
But I'm really excited about the choice of leaving.

2354
03:30:34,321 --> 03:30:37,542
I was shocked the morning I woke up and I heard the result.

2355
03:30:37,782 --> 03:30:41,584
After 24 hours of thinking about it, it was a, do you know what, we've just got to get on with this now.

2356
03:30:41,944 --> 03:30:43,725
The Congress has made a decision, let's do it.

2357
03:30:43,765 --> 03:30:47,868
So what is the positive we can drive from leaving Europe?

2358
03:30:48,168 --> 03:30:51,169
And that is that we have to potentially build our own future.

2359
03:30:51,650 --> 03:30:56,112
Why I voted to remain was purely from the employment point of view.

2360
03:30:56,192 --> 03:31:00,794
Well I was going to say there are restaurateurs already going public saying that they are losing staff.

2361
03:31:01,134 --> 03:31:10,897
There are people saying the double whammy of losing key staff who are heading for home or not applying for jobs that have become vacant from Europe.

2362
03:31:10,937 --> 03:31:17,639
The pool of talented European staff who are available to British restaurants is diminishing.

2363
03:31:17,979 --> 03:31:23,341
But also the pound is much weaker and that's affecting you as you import some of your foodstuff.

2364
03:31:23,421 --> 03:31:26,082
So it's a double whammy and some restaurateurs are saying they may have to

2365
03:31:26,182 --> 03:31:26,542
close?

2366
03:31:26,843 --> 03:31:54,973
From a point of view of what we purchased, unfortunately the customers are going to probably get a hit on that because you have to pay your bills, you have to pay your wages, but there's a really interesting twist to not having more of the European community coming to the UK to work and that is that we the Brits have got to get out of bed and work maybe a little bit harder and I think it's going to make us better employers and I think we need to change our approach a little bit more because what quality we have we're going to have to really take good care of it and secondly

